 		<h2>Some effective ways to use Coconut shells</h2>
 		<h5>Updated 10th Oct,2020</h5>
 		<img src="img/coconutp.jpg" alt="blog "/>
 		
 		<p>Coconut flesh is delicious and nutritious. The coconut shell has 
             uses too, and finding ways to repurpose coconut shells you've got 
             left over can prove an eco-friendly way to create a few things for 
             around the house that help you out.</p>
 	  </div>
 	  <div class="card">
 		<h1>1.) Use it as a Container</h1>
 		
 		<img src="img/coconutp1.jpg" alt="blog "/>
 		
 		<p> Use the coconut shell to keep trinkets, treasures and small items in.
              Things to keep inside might include rubber bands, keys, toys, pens 
              and pencils, twist ties, your stash of used plastic bags, etc. 
              Use the coconut shell to keep trinkets, treasures and small items in. 
              Things to keep inside might include rubber bands, keys, toys, pens and 
              pencils, twist ties, your stash of used plastic bags, etc.</p>

		<h1>2.) Use it as a Plant holder</h1>
		<img src="img/coconutp2.jpg" />

		<p>Grow a small plant in the coconut shell. While half a coconut shell can work, 
            having it cut about three quarters of its height is usually the best size 
            for a coconut shell plant holder. Drill or pierce some drainage holes in 
            the base of the shell first, and line with sphagnum moss.
        <br>
        <br>
        Hanging plant holders are another option</p>
			
		<h1>3.) Use it as a Bird feeder</h1>
		<img src="img/coconutp3.jpg" />

		<p>Turn into a hanging bird feeder. Drill some holes at even spaces around 
            the top and thread through some heavy twine or thin rope. Tie at the top 
            with a ring or similar to allow for hanging. Fill with birdseed and hang 
            in an appropriate place. Clean regularly.</p>


